19 SECTION 10. G.S. 14-69.3 reads as rewritten:
20 "§ 14-69.3. Arson or other unlawful burning that results in serious bodily injury or serious
21 injury to a firefighter, law enforcement officer, public safety officer or fire
22 investigator, or emergency medical technician.investigator.
23 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
24 (1) Emergency medical technician. – The term includes an emergency medical
25 technician, an advanced emergency medical technician, and an emergency
26 medical technician-paramedic, as those terms are defined in G.S. 131E-155.
27 (2) Fire investigator. – The term includes any person who, individually or as part
28 of an investigative team, has the responsibility and authority to determine the
29 origin, cause, or development of a fire or explosion.
30 (3) Public safety officer. – As defined in G.S. 14-34.7A.
31 (b) Offense Involving Serious Bodily Injury. – A Unless covered under some other
32 provision of law providing greater punishment, a person is guilty of a Class E felony if (i) the
33 person commits a felony under Article 15 of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes and a firefighter,
34 law enforcement officer, public safety officer or fire investigator, or emergency medical
35 technician investigator suffers serious bodily injury while discharging or attempting to discharge
36 official duties on the property, or proximate to the property, that is the subject of the firefighter's,
37 law enforcement officer's, fire investigator's, or emergency medical technician's public safety
38 officer's or fire investigator's discharge or attempt to discharge his or her respective duties.duties
39 or (ii) the person commits a felony under Article 15 of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes because
40 of the victim's status as a public safety officer or fire investigator and the public safety officer or
41 fire investigator suffers serious bodily injury.
42 (c) Offense Involving Serious Injury. – A Unless covered under some other provision of
